No, apparently not. The creature just snarled and tried to fly directly toward Thassalin. Fortunately, Thassalin, despite his size, was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi let out a scream as she nearly lost her grip on Thassalin's overly smooth scales.
"HOW CAN WE KILL HER?," screamed Nyssi.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEADS!"
"THIS WILL BE DIFFICULT!"
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle, getting closer to the mountain he called his home. The dark beast followed, but soon fell into panic when a fire beam struck her from behind. She hadn't noticed that she was no longer alone. She became even more panicked when Thassalin slowed down and then swung his tail at her head, knocking her off course.
Snarling and growling, it flew upward and spat into the air. Everything suddenly became dark, as if the monster had sucked the light from the sky and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he suddenly could no longer see anything, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree canopy before finally crashing into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen, and shot directly at him, dragging the black cloud with it.
"Kayel!" cried Tenuk as he slipped out of the cloud and began circling, searching for Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. "What should we do now? Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?"
Below, Nyssi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her peculiar, supernatural healing powers were already beginning to take effect. Unfortunately, this did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhaustedly against the only tree that hadn't collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made every effort to get close to Thassalin, but she could hardly see two meters ahead. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in this shadow, something screamed and screeched.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed beside Nyssi onto the earth and knocked her down. But she noticed that the tail was just swinging wildly and not attempting to hit her deliberately. The beast, or what little Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and clawed at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, struck the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gunshot cracked through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground, and lay motionless. The darkness around them dissolved, and they saw what had happened: standing on top of the beast was Kayel, holding his rifle heavily breathless.
“That was… the craziest shadow jump I've ever made… Thanto kat’olon…,” Kabel gasped for air. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy swirled around his body. But while he was still speaking, color returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their normal yellow color.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He used them rarely, because most found them eerie and quite frightening. But Nyssi had not known that Kayel could use these powers in any kind of darkness. And the way Kayel was acting, he apparently was also quite surprised.
“Are you okay?” Nyssi blurted out.
“Yes, I'm fine. I've killed something, I'll be back to normal soon.” Kayel looked at his work, while Tenuk flew down, landed next to him, and resumed his normal spastic form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could better see what it was. Its skin was black as ravens and slimy, but the slime remained stuck to its body. It had four wings and four extremities, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns stood out from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell they were looking at, something screeched and jumped out from a nearby bush. It didn't reach them, however, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the monster to slide to a stop in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi didn't want to take any risks. She grabbed her shot gun, fired without thinking at its head, and the creature died right there.
“Oops…,” muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before awkwardly turning off the engine and getting out of the truck. “Uh, that wasn't really intended. Are you all okay?”
“You missed the whole action,” scolded Tenuk. “Where were you?”
“You all just left me behind. I came as fast as I could…,” sighed Retvik. “May I ask what terrible creatures these are?”
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had regained his composure. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not seriously injured.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTED! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES THAT WERE LEAVING HERE, WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS!"
"You mean the terrible God-Monster creature that we… helped kill?" stammered Tenuk.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT. Perhaps there are more. But I could not shoot in the head. I have no gun. And two against one is unfair, or?" Thassalin hobbled to Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO SKILLED IN KILLING WHOLE UNIVERSES."
"Um… thank you… I think…" Kayel shrugged. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged her shoulders. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the now definitely dead beasts. Then she pulled out her favorite weapon, the ornate Death God dagger, and began cutting off one of the beast's horns. Afterwards, she moved on to the second. But just as Nyssi finished, the beasts suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ash in seconds. The same happened to the horns she had cut off.
"So, this is both practical and impractical…," sighed Nyssi. "But at least I have the photos, hopefully."
